atment against discogenic pain that will effectively remove the pain and the need for spinal fusion. Stayble’s treatment offers the patient a completely new way to treat its chronic low back pain and will drastically change the way surgeons treat cLBP.\r\n\r\nStayble’s treatment will be a breakthrough with its efficacy and simplicity compare to today’s complex and ineffective treatment regimes.\r\n\r\nThe treatment is based on an existing drug substance giving Stayble access to existing safety data and the possibility to buy the substance off the shelf. This will generate a shorter time to market at a much lower risk than conventional pharmaceutical development.\r\n\r\nThe injection treatment works in the way of fully transform the disc centre from being a liquid into connective tissue, as shown in the figure below. Either a spine surgeon or a radiologist will perform the treatment.\r\n\r\nThe transformation of the disc centre will remove the pain-causing component (the leakage) and in a simple, cost-saving and minimally-invasive (according to the classification of spinal interventions) way eliminate the pain for the patients. The treatment is assumed to be effective within 4 weeks, last the patient’s entire life and require no need for rehabilitation.\r\n\r\nWith this treatment, Stayble is first to directly target the pain provoking mechanism behind discogenic low back pain, allowing the patient to be pain free. Stayble will be able to fulfil the need of a new take-on towards treatment of discogenic pain where there today are very few actors actually able to remove the patient’s pain, for comparison, see Competition.\r\n<h3>Stayble’s treatment in short</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Minimally-invasive single injection based treatment</li>\r\n	<li>Directly targeting the pain provoking mechanism</li>\r\n	<li><span style="line-height: 1.5;">Does not require the patient to stay in the hospital</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="line-height: 1.5;">Estimated to have low COGS</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf the treatment fails to reduce the pain it will not block other treatment options\r\n\r\nIs estimated to be efficient within 4 weeks\r\n<h2>Pre-clinical verification of the concept</h2>\r\nStayble has successfully demonstrated that an injection of its treatment transforms the disc centre into connective tissue, as indicated by the red lines in the picture of a treated, disc below. This transformation was demonstrated in a pig model. The mechanisms and dose-response has been confirmed in vitro by adding the substance to cell lines and measuring the amount of connective tissue produced.', 'Technology', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '43-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-02-17 13:22:57', '2015-02-17 13:22:57', '', 43, 'http://localhost/phptest/stayble-old/43-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
