(253, 1, '2015-02-17 20:22:31', '2015-02-17 20:22:31', '<p class="ingress">Stayble therapeutics is developing a minimally invasive injection-based treatment against chronic low back pain triggered by tears in the disc caused by disc degeneration. Stayble offer a solution that actually will remove the pain for the patients without the need for surgery.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Market</h2>\r\n[ezcol_1half]\r\n\r\nThe initial market for Stayble will be patients that are scheduled to undergo a spinal fusion and are suffering from discogenic pain caused by disc degeneration (often referred as degenerative disc disease) with a confirmed leakage from the disc. This patient group consist of approximately 130 000 fusions performed in the US and EU of which around 100 000 patients will be treatable with Stayble''s product. The reason for choosing this segment as a starting point is that it is a good market to verify the concept and a segment where we will be able to charge a high product price, see Health economic.\r\n\r\n[/ezcol_1half]\r\n\r\n[ezcol_1half]\r\n\r\nIn a second phase the aim is to target the market of patients suffering from moderate discogenic pain for whom the risks and the costs associated with a spinal fusion exceeds the likely benefit. This will be a much larger patient group but where we will be harder to get initial acceptance and where the pricing will be lower.\r\n\r\n[/ezcol_1half]\r\n\r\n[ezcol_end_both]\r\n<h2>Current treatments</h2>\r\nThere is currently no available treatment that targets the pain-provoking component of discogenic pain as Stayble''s does. Competition, however, relates to more advanced fusion devices and new types of implants, which only incrementally improve the outcome for the patient.\r\n<h2>Pricing</h2>\r\n[ezcol_1half]\r\n\r\nA pricing comparison has been made comparing with the cost for the minimally invasive treatments identified in Competition above. The cost for a steroid injection is approximately €100 for the product and around €500 for the actual procedure, yielding a total cost of €600 per treatment. Patients undergo this type of treatment 3 times per year (every year) at a cost of €1800. Thermal procedures are more expensive with a cost for the disposable needle of around €800 and a procedure cost of €6000. It is important to remember that the compared treatments (steroids and thermal energy) are not considered to be a cure and needs to be repeated to take away the pain. The only cure is the fusion, at a cost of approximately €22 000.\r\n\r\n[/ezcol_1half]\r\n\r\n[ezcol_1half]\r\n\r\nStayble''s procedure cost is estimated to around €1300 according to our health economic assessment, see below. The pricing for the product is estimated to between €3-5000, yielding a lower total cost than thermal energy and a similar cost to three year treatment with steroids but actually removing the pain.\r\n\r\n100 000 patients are being fused for this specific problem. All can be treated by Stayble.\r\n\r\n[/ezcol_1half]\r\n\r\n[ezcol_end_both]\r\n<h2>Market penetration and estimated peak sale</h2>\r\n[ezcol_1half]\r\n\r\nThe market penetration is estimated to start rather slow to gain acceptance of the new treatment procedure on the market. This due to that spinal surgeons are a relatively conservative group. It is, however, very well connected with a large community with will mean that once Stayble''s treatment will be accepted on the market by the main drivers we estimate a more rapid adoption.\r\n\r\nStayble estimate that after 6 years on the market have approximately 33 % of the market share. This segment involves in the initial market focus approximately 32 000 patients (US, EU).\r\n\r\nAt a sales price of €4000 this equals to a yearly income of 128MEURO just in the segment of fusions (towards degenerative disc disease) today. When the product has been accepted on the market we estimate an extensive increase in usage towards a broader indication\r\n\r\n[/ezcol_1half]\r\n\r\n[ezcol_1half]\r\n\r\n<a href="http://localhost/phptest/stayble-old/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/gubbar.png"><img class=" size-full wp-image-241 aligncenter" src="http://localhost/phptest/stayble-old/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/gubbar.png" alt="gubbar" width="300" height="289" /></a>\r\n\r\n[/ezcol_1half]\r\n\r\n[ezcol_end_both]\r\n<h2>Intellectual Property</h2>\r\nStayble has in March 20th 2014 applied for a patent for the use of our substance (in the US a use patent and in the EU a pharmaceutical product patent according to the EPO legislation) for the treatment of intervertebral discs (discs in the spine).\r\n\r\nPrior to the application, a detailed analysis of the freedom to operate (FTO) was performed in collaboration with Awapatent. The result from this study is that the invention is patentable and that there is freedom to operate. This was further evaluated by Anders Bergman, Profora who performed a second opinion of the work done by Awapatent with the same conclusion that the invention is patentable, has an inventive step and freedom to operate.\r\n<h2>Based on an existing substance</h2>\r\nOne important success factor relating to the development of Stayble’s treatment is that it is based on an existing drug substance giving us access to available data relating to toxicology of the substance, previous data relating to adverse effects and methods of analysing levels in human tissue and blood. This in combination leads to a decrease development time, risk and cost throughout the development.\r\n<h2>Financing</h2>\r\nStayble is currently financed by a Vinnova (Sweden''s innovation agency) grant of €215 000 awarded in August 2014. The funds are distributed over a period of 18 months and provide a cornerstone in the funding of Stayble until January 2016. In addition Stayble was awarded a research grant of €50 000 in September 2014.\r\n<h3>The following actors have previously funded Stayble:</h3>\r\n[ezcol_2third]\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Encubator AB</li>\r\n	<li>Vinnova</li>\r\n	<li>Almi</li>\r\n	<li>Innovationskontor Väst</li>\r\n	<li>FRF-stiftelsen</li>\r\n	<li>GU Holding</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/ezcol_2third]\r\n\r\n[ezcol_1third]\r\n\r\n<a href="http://localhost/phptest/stayble-old/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/bubbla.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-248 size-medium" src="http://localhost/phptest/stayble-old/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/bubbla-281x300.png" alt="bubbla" width="281" height="300" /></a>\r\n\r\n[/ezcol_1third]\r\n\r\n[ezcol_end_both]\r\n\r\nTo be able to accelerate the development towards an application for clinical trials Stayble is currently searching for further financing, initially 0,5 MEUR. The total cost for development until PoC in humans is estimated to 2,9 MEUR divided into three different financing rounds according to the graphics below. For a more detailed description see coming headlines.\r\n\r\nThe calculations relating to the development cost has been benchmarked with similar biotech start-ups that has gone through a similar development process until PoC in humans.\r\n\r\nBusiness plan upon request.', 'Investors', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '45-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-02-17 20:22:31', '2015-02-17 20:22:31', '', 45, 'http://localhost/phptest/stayble-old/45-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(254, 1, '2015-02-17 20:31:57', '2015-02-17 20:31:57', '<p class="ingress">Stayble therapeutics is developing a minimally invasive injection-based treatment against chronic low back pain triggered by tears in the disc caused by disc degeneration. Stayble offer a solution that actually will remove the pain for the patients without the need for surgery.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>The Problem</h2>\r\nChronic low back pain is caused by leakage of disc liquid cLBP is a disabling and extremely expensive condition for the healthcare sector and for society, affecting millions of patients and generating annual total costs exceeding €80 billion in the US alones1. It is well acknowledged that the cause of pain is unknown for 90-95% of all cases of cLBP, described as idiopathic low back pain. This makes cLBP very difficult to address therapeutically.\r\n\r\n[ezcol_1half]\r\n\r\nHowever, recently it was established that a major cause of pain result from leakage of disc material through tears of the degenerating (aging) disc often referred to as discogenic pain 2–4. The pro-inflammatory disc material thus comes in contact with the nerves on the outer surface of the disc, which is known to produce pain in the lower back if stimulated 5,6. A disc consists of two parts; the liquid disc centre and the disc wall. Today, spinal fusion is the only available treatment for patients with discogenic pain, who do not respond to the usual conservative treatment with painkillers and physiotherapy.\r\n\r\n[/ezcol_1half]\r\n\r\n[ezcol_1half]\r\n\r\nIt is an ineffective, invasive and by many a questioned procedure with rehabilitation of up to 6 months and accompanying work absence of up to 2 years.\r\n\r\nIn addition according to interviewed surgeons only 60% of the patients can expect to get better after the treatment whereas 24% remain unchanged and 16% become worse.\r\n\r\n[/ezcol_1half]\r\n\r\n[ezcol_end_both]\r\n<h2>Our solution</h2>\r\nStayble Therapeutics (Stayble) is developing an injection-based treatment against discogenic pain that will effectively remove the pain and the need for spinal fusion. Stayble’s treatment offers the patient a completely new way to treat its chronic low back pain and will drastically change the way surgeons treat cLBP.\r\n\r\nStayble’s treatment will be a breakthrough with its efficacy and simplicity compare to today’s complex and ineffective treatment regimes.\r\n\r\nThe treatment is based on an existing drug substance giving Stayble access to existing safety data and the possibility to buy the substance off the shelf. This will generate a shorter time to market at a much lower risk than conventional pharmaceutical development.\r\n\r\nThe injection treatment works in the way of fully transform the disc centre from being a liquid into connective tissue, as shown in the figure below. Either a spine surgeon or a radiologist will perform the treatment.\r\n\r\n[ezcol_1half]\r\n\r\nThe transformation of the disc centre will remove the pain-causing component (the leakage) and in a simple, cost-saving and minimally-invasive (according to the classification of spinal interventions) way eliminate the pain for the patients. The treatment is assumed to be effective within 4 weeks, last the patient’s entire life and require no need for rehabilitation.\r\n\r\n[/ezcol_1half]\r\n\r\n[ezcol_1half]\r\n\r\nWith this treatment, Stayble is first to directly target the pain provoking mechanism behind discogenic low back pain, allowing the patient to be pain free. Stayble will be able to fulfil the need of a new take-on towards treatment of discogenic pain where there today are very few actors actually able to remove the patient’s pain, for comparison, see Competition.\r\n\r\n[/ezcol_1half]\r\n\r\n[ezcol_end_both]\r\n<h2>Stayble’s treatment in short</h2>\r\n[ezcol_2third]\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Minimally-invasive single injection based treatment</li>\r\n	<li>Directly targeting the pain provoking mechanism</li>\r\n	<li>Does not require the patient to stay in the hospital</li>\r\n	<li>Estimated to have low COGS</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/ezcol_2third]\r\n\r\n[ezcol_1third]\r\n\r\n<a href="http://localhost/phptest/stayble-old/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/disk.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-246" src="http://localhost/phptest/stayble-old/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/disk.png" alt="disk" width="300" height="196" /></a>\r\n\r\n[/ezcol_1third]\r\n\r\n[ezcol_end_both]\r\n\r\nIf the treatment fails to reduce the pain it will not block other treatment options\r\n\r\nIs estimated to be efficient within 4 weeks\r\n<h2>Pre-clinical verification of the concept</h2>\r\nStayble has successfully demonstrated that an injection of its treatment transforms the disc centre into connective tissue, as indicated by the red lines in the picture of a treated, disc below. This transformation was demonstrated in a pig model. The mechanisms and dose-response has been confirmed in vitro by adding the substance to cell lines and measuring the amount of connective tissue produced.', 'Technology', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '43-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-02-17 20:31:57', '2015-02-17 20:31:57', '', 43, 'http://localhost/phptest/stayble-old/43-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
